Git Cmdline tools

# Manually create the global configuration file
touch ~/.gitconfig


Initialize a Git Repository
git init

# Set global user name and email
git config --global user.name "Abhilash Kolusu"
git config --global user.email "AbhilashKolusu@gmail.com"

# Verify the global configuration
git config --list --global
git config --list --local

Setup the SSH Keys 

# Generate a new SSH key
ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096 -C "AbhilashKolusu@gmail.com"

# Start the SSH agent
eval "$(ssh-agent -s)"

# Create the SSH directory if it doesn't exist
mkdir -p ~/.ssh

# Add your SSH private key to the SSH agent
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_rsa

# Copy the contents of your public key to the clipboard
pbcopy < ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub

# add the SSH key to the ssh-agent
Add the SSH Key to GitHub
Go to GitHub and sign in.
Click your profile picture in the top-right and go to Settings.
In the left sidebar, click SSH and GPG keys.
Click New SSH key.
Title: Add a label like "MacBook-Air SSH Key".
Key: Paste the SSH key you copied.
Click Add SSH key and confirm with your password if prompted.

# Test your SSH connection to GitHub
ssh -T git@github.com



# Git Commands Cheat Sheet

## Initialize and Clone
- `git init`
- `git clone git@github.com:user/repo.git`

## Staging and Committing
- `git status`
- `git add file_name`
- `git add .`
- `git commit -m "Commit message"`
-  git commit --amend --no-edit

## Branching
- `git branch branch_name`
- `git checkout branch_name`
- `git checkout -b branch_name`
- `git branch`
- `git branch -d branch_name`

## Push and Pull
- `git remote add origin git@github.com:user/repo.git`
- `git push origin branch_name`
- `git push -u origin main`
- `git pull origin branch_name`
- `git fetch`

## Merging and Rebasing
- `git merge branch_name`
- `git rebase branch_name`
git rebase -i HEAD~3

## Undoing Changes
- `git reset file_name`
- `git checkout -- file_name`
- `git commit --amend`

## Logs and Diffs
- `git log`
- `git diff`

## Tags
- `git tag tag_name`
- `git push origin tag_name`

## prune
- git prune



## Advanced Git Commands
- `git stash` – Save changes temporarily.
- `git stash pop` – Apply stashed changes.
- `git cherry-pick <commit>` – Apply a specific commit.
- `git rebase -i HEAD~n` – Interactive rebase (squash, edit commits).
- `git reflog` – View history of HEAD changes.
- `git reset --hard <commit>` – Reset to a specific commit.
- `git revert <commit>` – Revert a specific commit.
- `git bisect start` – Start binary search for bugs.
- `git bisect good <commit>` – Mark commit as good.
- `git bisect bad <commit>` – Mark commit as bad.
- `git worktree add ../new-branch branch_name` – Create a new working tree.
- `git blame file_name` – Show who made each line change.
- `git shortlog -sn` – Summary of contributions.